The '''Black Eight Squadron''' was an elite [[Galactic Empire/Legends|Imperial]] [[Squadron/Legends|military unit]] composed of [[TIE pilot|pilots]] who were highly trained in flying [[TIE/ln space superiority starfighter/Legends|TIE/LN starfighters]] and [[TIE/sa tactical bomber/Legends|TIE/sa bombers]] for the [[Imperial Navy/Legends|Imperial Navy]]. The [[Sith Lord/Legends|Sith Lord]] [[Anakin Skywalker/Legends|Darth Vader]] maintained the squadron under his direct command, and personally supervised the selection of its lead [[Pilot/Legends|pilot]]. [[Captain/Legends|Captain]] [[Juno Eclipse/Legends|Juno Eclipse]] and other [[Ace/Legends|ace]] pilots with exceptional flight records were assigned to Vader's personal squadron.

After the [[Battle of Yavin/Legends|Battle of Yavin]], [[Darth/Legends|Darth]] Vader reorganized the Black Eight Squadron into a group of convicted pilots led by [[Nas Ghent]], a former ace pilot of the [[Confederacy of Independent Systems/Legends|Confederacy of Independent Systems]]. By [[1 ABY/Legends|1 ABY]], the squadron was headquartered on the [[Imperial-class Star Destroyer/Legends|''Imperial''-class Star Destroyer]] [[Crucible (Imperial-class)|''Crucible'']] as a result of the [[Alliance to Restore the Republic/Legends|Rebel Alliance's]] victories in minor space battles.

==History==
===Origin===
In the aftermath of the [[Clone Wars/Legends|Clone Wars]], the [[Sith Lord/Legends|Sith Lord]] [[Anakin Skywalker/Legends|Darth Vader]] emerged as the [[Supreme Commander (Galactic Empire)/Legends|Supreme Commander]] of the [[Imperial Military/Legends|military forces]] of the newly formed [[Galactic Empire/Legends|Galactic Empire]].<ref name="ROTS">{{Film|III}}</ref> In addition to the [[501st Legion/Legends|501st Legion]],<ref name="BFII">''[[Star Wars: Battlefront II]]''</ref> the Black Eight [[Squadron/Legends|Squadron]] was also under the personal command of the [[Dark Lord of the Sith/Legends|Dark Lord of the Sith]]. Under [[Darth/Legends|Darth]] Vader's leadership, the Black Eight developed into an elite unit in the [[Imperial Navy/Legends|Imperial Navy]] and was especially noted for their obedience and brutality. Vader carefully maintained the unit's composition by personally handling the selection of its leaders and [[TIE pilot]]s, mainly to ensure that the squadron continued to live up to its reputation. As such, service within the Black Eight was brief for all members, a fact obscured by the mystique surrounding their highly classified assignments. Its members never revealed the identities of their wingmates or the details of their missions; outsiders never speculated about the squadron either. The core objective for any Black Eight [[Pilot/Legends|pilot]] was to give Vader success in every mission, no matter the circumstance.<ref name="TFUn" />

===Bombing of Callos===
{{Quote|It's a dead world now.|Juno Eclipse, referring to the consequences of her squadron's actions on Callos|<ref name="vg">''[[Star Wars: The Force Unleashed]]''</ref>}}
[[File:JunoEclipseHS-TFU.png|thumb|left|200px|Captain Juno Eclipse, the destroyer of Callos]]
By the [[Standard year/Legends|year]] [[3 BBY/Legends|3 BBY]], the Black Eight Squadron's [[Commander/Legends|commander]] was [[Juno Eclipse/Legends|Juno Eclipse]], a [[Human/Legends|Human]] [[Gender/Legends|female]] [[Imperial officer/Legends|officer]] who joined the Imperial Navy after graduating as the youngest [[Cadet/Legends|cadet]] in the history of the [[Corulag Academy]]. Impressed by the young woman's record for fidelity and competence, Darth Vader appointed [[Captain/Legends|Captain]] Eclipse as squadron leader. The wingmates under her command included [[Cartha|"Chaser" Cartha]], [["Youngster"/Legends|Youngster]] and [[Redline]]. Eclipse regarded the Black Eight Squadron as an elite unit and was immensely proud to serve as its commanding officer.<ref name="TFUn" />

Eclipse's pride in the Black Eight Squadron was brief, however. Shortly after her promotion, the Black Eight was deployed on a mission to [[Bombing of Callos|invade]] the [[Planet/Legends|planet]] [[Callos]]. Although she followed her initial orders to the letter, conducting a [[Bomb/Legends|bombing]] raid over [[Callos resistance|enemy targets]], her reaction to Darth Vader's next order was one of shock and apprehension. The [[Callosian]]s' ability to offer further resistance was effectively broken, but the [[Sith/Legends|Sith]] Lord instructed the Black Eight Squadron to proceed with a full bombardment on the planet's defenseless inhabitants. [[Force sense/Legends|Sensing]] her disapproval, Vader instead ordered Eclipse's squadron to destroy Callos's planetary reactor, and only then would he consider the mission a success. Eclipse complied with the new order, believing that she had averted genocide.<ref name="TFUn" />

The Black Eight fulfilled its mission objective with a surgical precision attack on the reactor; each strike found its target well before the defenses could be activated. However, the reactor's destruction unleashed pollutants into the planet's atmosphere, contaminating all of Callos and rendering it uninhabitable.<ref name="TFUn" />

===Post-Callos===
{{Quote|Handpicked by Lord Vader to lead his Black Eight Squadron, but later reassigned to a top secret project&mdash;|[[PROXY]], accessing Juno Eclipse's Imperial record|<ref name="TFUn" />}}
Following the destruction of Callos, Vader rotated Eclipse out of the Black Eight Squadron and selected her as the eighth pilot of his [[Galen Marek|secret apprentice's]] [[Starship/Legends|starship]], the ''[[Rogue Shadow]]''. Chaser was personally recommended by Eclipse as the next squadron leader, but was passed over in favor of Redline, a callous man whom Eclipse described as "psychopathic." Youngster, a pilot noted for his optimism, had followed Eclipse into the Black Eight and left to fly [[Transport/Legends|transport]] ships soon after her reassignment. In addition to Redline and Chaser, who remained in fourth place on the squadron's roster, only a third of Eclipse's teammates were still part of the Black Eight in [[2 BBY/Legends|2 BBY]]; another third was listed as [[Death/Legends|deceased]] while the remainder advanced via promotion in the military hierarchy.<ref name="TFUn" />

===The new Black Eight Squadron===
[[File:Nas_Ghent_TIE_pilot.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Nas Ghent, Separatist-turned-Imperial pilot]]
{{Quote|You're to find a group of independent thinkers who can operate outside of the Empire's bureaucracy. Pull them from the Imperial prison system if you have to.|Darth Vader, to Dorin Millavec|<ref name="Walking the Path That's Given">{{Tales|21|Walking the Path That's Given}}</ref>}}
The Black Eight Squadron was reorganized in [[1 ABY/Legends|1 ABY]] by Darth Vader during the [[Galactic Civil War/Legends|Galactic Civil War]]. In response to the [[Alliance to Restore the Republic/Legends|Rebel Alliance's]] unorthodox tactics, the Sith Lord chose to reform the Black Eight's composition by replacing its pilots with non-military personnel. Unattached to the Empire's cumbersome bureaucracy, Vader believed that the new Black Eight would be more effective as an unconventional unit, unhindered by the normal [[Imperial High Command/Legends|chain of command]]. The task of overseeing the squadron's development was entrusted to Commander [[Dorin Millavec]], the [[Starfighter/Legends|fighter]] operations officer of the [[Imperial-class Star Destroyer/Legends|Imperial Star Destroyer]] [[Crucible (Imperial-class)|''Crucible'']].<ref name="Tales21" />

In addition to the conscription of [[Nas Ghent]], a [[Smuggler/Legends|smuggler]] who previously served as a [[Confederacy of Independent Systems/Legends|Separatist]] pilot during the [[Cloning/Legends|Clone]] Wars, the rest of the squadron was composed of independent-minded pilots who could operate outside of the command structure. Those recruited into the squadron's ranks were chosen by Millavec, who had been told by Vader to search through the Imperial [[Prison/Legends|penitentiary]] system for ideal candidates. Although Millavec complied with Vader's orders, he harbored much resentment toward the pilots of Black Eight due to their renegade backgrounds. He especially hated Ghent because of the former Separatist's disdain for military discipline.<ref name="Tales21" />

Millavec, convinced that the Black Eight Squadron was a threat to his promotion prospects, secretly tried to sabotage Ghent's progress. While conducting a test flight, Millavec assigned Ghent an older [[TIE/ln space superiority starfighter|TIE/LN fighter]] without working weapons, and ordered the squadron's other pilots to kill their leader during his familiarization with the fighter. Ghent instead destroyed his wingmates, however and soon became reinvigorated as a pilot due to Millavec's duplicity. After Millavec excused his actions by claiming that the attack had been staged as a test by Vader, Ghent promised to establish the Black Eight Squadron as the best aerial unit in the Imperial Navy. As the rivalry grew between the two, Millavec released some of the most unstable psychopaths from incarceration and recruited them as Ghent's new wingmates in a new plot to [[Assassin/Legends|assassinate]] the wayward TIE pilot.<ref name="Tales21" />

==Organization==
Qualification to be a member of the squadron included loyalty and ruthlessness, the two defining traits of the most feared TIE fighter squadron in the Empire. One way to maintain the Squadron's characteristics was high turnover rate for its leaders and pilots. One leader commanded the Black Eight for a single [[Standard month/Legends|month]] before his rotation to another unit. His successor lasted briefly, and his own successor, Juno Eclipse, was a leader for even briefer time.<ref name="TFUn" />

Though pilots were obedient to the chain of command, Eclipse's and Youngster's apprehension to Vader's brutal tactics led to their removal from the Black Eight; Chaser shared same skepticism, and although he remained with the squadron, he was effectively barred from rising beyond fourth place. Those who possessed no ethical concerns for the use of excess force were rewarded with advancement, such as Redline who succeeded Eclipse as squadron leader. Although the three former squadron leaders were listed as deceased by 2 BBY, Eclipse remained alive and was assigned as personal pilot to [[Galen Marek|Starkiller]].<ref name="TFUn" />

The new structure of the Black Eight Squadron under Nas Ghent's leadership reflected the unit's detachment from the chain of command. In accordance with Darth Vader's wishes, the squadron comprised rogue pilots whose disregard for authority was seen as an unconventional asset by the Dark Lord of the Sith.<ref name="Tales21" />

The Black Eight Squadron's primary complement was TIE/LN starfighters and TIE/sa bombers, although they have used at least one [[TIE/ca Punisher/Legends|TIE/IT Interdictor starfighter]] during their missions.<ref name="TIE Punisher Expansion Pack">{{FFGXW|set=TIE Punisher Expansion Pack|cardname=Black Eight Sq. Pilot}}</ref>

==Behind the scenes==
{{Quote|Handpicked by Lord Vader to lead his Black Five Squadron, but later reassigned to a top secret project&mdash;|[[PROXY]]|<ref name="vg" />}}
[[Jeremy Barlow]] hinted that a future [[Star Wars: Rebellion (comic series)|''Rebellion'']] arc could feature Ghent recruiting [[BoShek/Legends|BoShek]] into the squadron.<ref name="DHBoards">{{DHBoards|url=viewtopic.php?t=9774&start=0|thread=Nas Ghent's story|user=[[Jeremy Barlow]]|date=2006-08-07|time=12:13 PM|quote=Hmm, let's see? last we saw Nas Ghent, he was sent to recruit pilots from the Imperial prison system, which also happens to be where our second favorite smuggler Boshek was headed. I wonder if that's what Brandon and I are cooking up for an upcoming Rebellion arc. Naw, couldn't be...}}</ref> However, ''Rebellion'' was later cancelled in favor of ''[[Star Wars: Invasion]]''.

There is a discrepancy regarding which squadron [[Juno Eclipse/Legends|Juno Eclipse]] served with prior to her reassignment to the ''[[Rogue Shadow]]''. In the [[Star Wars: The Force Unleashed|video game]] version of ''[[Star Wars: The Force Unleashed]]'', both [[PROXY]] and Eclipse's Databank profile state that she was the leader of the "Black Five Squadron," a fact also mentioned in the game's [[Star Wars: The Force Unleashed II|sequel]]. Yet the [[Star Wars: The Force Unleashed (novelization)|first]] and [[Star Wars: The Force Unleashed II (novelization)|second]] novelizations state that her unit was the Black Eight Squadron.<ref name="TFUn" /><ref name="TFUIIn">[[Star Wars: The Force Unleashed II (novelization)|''Star Wars: The Force Unleashed II'' novelization]]</ref> Because novelizations supersede video games in [[Star Wars Legends|''Star Wars'' Legends]], this article refers to Eclipse as the leader of the Black Eight rather than the Black Five.

